{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585199"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:05:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:05:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14929"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14929"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.17,0.24,0.24,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7617"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66015"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7617"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14929"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51466"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18626"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18629"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66015"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E and other mycobacterial species are characterised by their unusually slow growth rates compared to common bacterial pathogens. This has significant implications for both diagnosis and treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the typical generation time for mycobacterial cell division?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["20-30 minutes","2-4 hours","24 hours","48 hours","7 days"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMycobacteria are extremely slow-growing organisms with a generation time of \u003Cstrong\u003E24 hours\u003C/strong\u003E. This is in stark contrast to most bacteria like \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E which divide every \u003Cstrong\u003E20-30 minutes\u003C/strong\u003E under optimal conditions. Generation times of \u003Cstrong\u003E2-4 hours\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003E48 hours\u003C/strong\u003E, or \u003Cstrong\u003E7 days\u003C/strong\u003E are either too fast or too slow for typical mycobacterial species.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe slow growth rate has several important clinical implications:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EExtended treatment courses are required for effective therapy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELaboratory cultures take weeks to grow for diagnosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EChronic nature of infections develops due to slow bacterial replication\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETraditional susceptibility testing is delayed\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHost immune responses may be altered by the slow growth pattern\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Mycobacteria have extremely slow generation times of 24 hours compared to most bacteria which divide every 20-30 minutes","The slow growth rate of mycobacteria contributes to their chronic nature and treatment challenges","Slow bacterial growth requires extended antibiotic treatment courses and delays laboratory diagnosis"],"references":["Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Uh\u00eda I, Williams KJ, Shahrezaei V, Robertson BD. Mycobacterial Growth. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Med. 2015 May 8;5(10):a021097. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a021097. PMID: 25957314; PMCID: PMC4588137.","Cook GM, Berney M, Gebhard S, Heinemann M, Cox RA, Danilchanka O, Niederweis M. Physiology of mycobacteria. Adv Microb Physiol. 2009;55:81-182, 318-9. doi: 10.1016/S0065-2911(09)05502-7. PMID: 19573696; PMCID: PMC3728839."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51466"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14929"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51466"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-28T19:08:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-28T19:10:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7617"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66015"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4927"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":n